1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,775
We can look at math from two

2
00:00:01,875 --> 00:00:05,594
different points of view. Syntactically and Semantically.

3
00:00:06,666 --> 00:00:10,001
The world of syntax is a formal and mechanical world

4
00:00:10,101 --> 00:00:13,436
where truth is given by proofs in a formal calculus.

5
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,817
Which is just a specific set of axioms

6
00:00:16,933 --> 00:00:19,849
written in a formal language, which can be combined

7
00:00:19,949 --> 00:00:23,337
according to certain rules of inference to generate proofs.

8
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,856
The semantics is the intuitive world in which the symbols

9
00:00:27,956 --> 00:00:32,020
of our logical language get interpreted into. Similar to how

10
00:00:32,120 --> 00:00:36,463
English words are just words which describe things that actually

11
00:00:36,563 --> 00:00:40,211
exist in the world. If viewed platonically, we can see

12
00:00:40,311 --> 00:00:46,249
mathematical formulas as describing properties of pre-existing structures which enhabit

13
00:00:46,349 --> 00:00:47,984
a perfect world of forms.

14
00:00:48,133 --> 00:00:52,014
This platonistic view of math is not shared by everyone. Some

15
00:00:52,114 --> 00:00:55,604
hold a formalist view of math, in which they ignore the

16
00:00:55,704 --> 00:00:59,912
semantic side of math choosing instead to work entirely within the

17
00:01:00,012 --> 00:01:04,350
confines of syntax. Others hold a constructivist view of math, where

18
00:01:04,450 --> 00:01:07,614
we have to be able to construct or at least define

19
00:01:07,714 --> 00:01:11,203
a mathematical object before we can say that it exists.

20
00:01:11,266 --> 00:01:14,647
But the branch of mathematics which deals with the relation

21
00:01:14,747 --> 00:01:18,305
between the syntax and the semantics --known as Model Theory--

22
00:01:18,405 --> 00:01:21,667
makes the most sense when viewed from the platonic world.

23
00:01:21,733 --> 00:01:25,865
There are different languages within which we can define our logic:

24
00:01:25,933 --> 00:01:28,889
Propositional or 0th order logic,

25
00:01:28,933 --> 00:01:30,949
FOL

26
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,609
and finally Higher OL's.

27
00:01:34,666 --> 00:01:39,124
Of these FOL is used to build or define mathematics. This is because

28
00:01:39,224 --> 00:01:44,619
FOL is strong enough to describe most mathematical structures well enough, and not

29
00:01:44,719 --> 00:01:49,177
so strong that we can no longer define a complete and sound calculus

30
00:01:49,277 --> 00:01:52,930
for it. We will see what this means later in this video.

31
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:54,889
But, we will start simple by

32
00:01:54,989 --> 00:01:58,228
understanding the basic of propositional logic.

